  <COMMENT line1="1999" col1="1" line2="1999" col2="37" start="465768" end="465804">#' Replace outliers with trimmed mean</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2000" col1="1" line2="2000" col2="2" start="466001" end="466002">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2001" col1="1" line2="2001" col2="74" start="466234" end="466307">#' Note that this function is called within \code{\link{DESeq}}, so is not</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2002" col1="1" line2="2002" col2="90" start="466467" end="466556">#' necessary to call on top of a \code{DESeq} call. See the \code{minReplicatesForReplace}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2003" col1="1" line2="2003" col2="45" start="466700" end="466744">#' argument documented in \code{link{DESeq}}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2004" col1="1" line2="2004" col2="3" start="466933" end="466935">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2005" col1="1" line2="2005" col2="77" start="467166" end="467242">#' This function replaces outlier counts flagged by extreme Cook's distances,</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2006" col1="1" line2="2006" col2="69" start="467399" end="467467">#' as calculated by \code{\link{DESeq}}, \code{\link{nbinomWaldTest}}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2007" col1="1" line2="2007" col2="72" start="467632" end="467703">#' or \code{\link{nbinomLRT}}, with values predicted by the trimmed mean</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2008" col1="1" line2="2008" col2="74" start="467865" end="467938">#' over all samples (and adjusted by size factor or normalization factor).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2009" col1="1" line2="2009" col2="81" start="468098" end="468178">#' This function replaces the counts in the matrix returned by \code{counts(dds)}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2010" col1="1" line2="2010" col2="81" start="468331" end="468411">#' and the Cook's distances in \code{assays(dds)[["cooks"]]}. Original counts are</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2011" col1="1" line2="2011" col2="55" start="468564" end="468618">#' preserved in \code{assays(dds)[["originalCounts"]]}.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2012" col1="1" line2="2012" col2="3" start="468797" end="468799">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2013" col1="1" line2="2013" col2="74" start="469030" end="469103">#' The \code{\link{DESeq}} function calculates a diagnostic measure called</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2014" col1="1" line2="2014" col2="77" start="469263" end="469339">#' Cook's distance for every gene and every sample. The \code{\link{results}}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2015" col1="1" line2="2015" col2="71" start="469496" end="469566">#' function then sets the p-values to \code{NA} for genes which contain</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2016" col1="1" line2="2016" col2="71" start="469729" end="469799">#' an outlying count as defined by a Cook's distance above a threshold.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2017" col1="1" line2="2017" col2="85" start="469962" end="470046">#' With many degrees of freedom, i.e. many more samples than number of parameters to </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2018" col1="1" line2="2018" col2="82" start="470195" end="470276">#' be estimated-- it might be undesirable to remove entire genes from the analysis</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2019" col1="1" line2="2019" col2="58" start="470428" end="470485">#' just because their data include a single count outlier.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2020" col1="1" line2="2020" col2="57" start="470661" end="470717">#' An alternate strategy is to replace the outlier counts</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2021" col1="1" line2="2021" col2="87" start="470894" end="470980">#' with the trimmed mean over all samples, adjusted by the size factor or normalization</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2022" col1="1" line2="2022" col2="82" start="471127" end="471208">#' factor for that sample. The following simple function performs this replacement</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2023" col1="1" line2="2023" col2="76" start="471360" end="471435">#' for the user, for samples which have at least \code{minReplicates} number</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2024" col1="1" line2="2024" col2="41" start="471593" end="471633">#' of replicates (including that sample).</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2025" col1="1" line2="2025" col2="62" start="471826" end="471887">#' For more information on Cook's distance, please see the two</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2026" col1="1" line2="2026" col2="89" start="472059" end="472147">#' sections of the vignette: 'Dealing with count outliers' and 'Count outlier detection'.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2027" col1="1" line2="2027" col2="3" start="472292" end="472294">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2028" col1="1" line2="2028" col2="75" start="472525" end="472599">#' @param object a DESeqDataSet object, which has already been processed by</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2029" col1="1" line2="2029" col2="77" start="472758" end="472834">#' either DESeq, nbinomWaldTest or nbinomLRT, and therefore contains a matrix</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2030" col1="1" line2="2030" col2="88" start="472991" end="473078">#' contained in \code{assays(dds)[["cooks"]]}. These are the Cook's distances which will</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2031" col1="1" line2="2031" col2="36" start="473224" end="473259">#' be used to define outlier counts.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2032" col1="1" line2="2032" col2="73" start="473457" end="473529">#' @param trim the fraction (0 to 0.5) of observations to be trimmed from</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2033" col1="1" line2="2033" col2="75" start="473690" end="473764">#' each end of the normalized counts for a gene before the mean is computed</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2034" col1="1" line2="2034" col2="75" start="473923" end="473997">#' @param cooksCutoff the threshold for defining an outlier to be replaced.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2035" col1="1" line2="2035" col2="75" start="474156" end="474230">#' Defaults to the .99 quantile of the F(p, m - p) distribution, where p is</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2036" col1="1" line2="2036" col2="59" start="474389" end="474447">#' the number of parameters and m is the number of samples.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2037" col1="1" line2="2037" col2="85" start="474622" end="474706">#' @param minReplicates the minimum number of replicate samples necessary to consider</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2038" col1="1" line2="2038" col2="92" start="474855" end="474946">#' a sample eligible for replacement (including itself). Outlier counts will not be replaced</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2039" col1="1" line2="2039" col2="75" start="475088" end="475162">#' if the sample is in a cell which has less than minReplicates replicates.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2040" col1="1" line2="2040" col2="70" start="475321" end="475390">#' @param whichSamples optional, a numeric or logical index to specify</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2041" col1="1" line2="2041" col2="84" start="475554" end="475637">#' which samples should have outliers replaced. if missing, this is determined using</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2042" col1="1" line2="2042" col2="17" start="475787" end="475803">#' minReplicates.</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2043" col1="1" line2="2043" col2="2" start="476020" end="476021">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2044" col1="1" line2="2044" col2="31" start="476253" end="476283">#' @seealso \code{\link{DESeq}}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2045" col1="1" line2="2045" col2="2" start="476486" end="476487">#'</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2046" col1="1" line2="2046" col2="42" start="476719" end="476760">#' @aliases replaceOutliersWithTrimmedMean</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2047" col1="1" line2="2047" col2="3" start="476952" end="476954">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2048" col1="1" line2="2048" col2="70" start="477185" end="477254">#' @return a DESeqDataSet with replaced counts in the slot returned by</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2049" col1="1" line2="2049" col2="60" start="477418" end="477477">#' \code{\link{counts}} and the original counts preserved in</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2050" col1="1" line2="2050" col2="41" start="477651" end="477691">#' \code{assays(dds)[["originalCounts"]]}</COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2051" col1="1" line2="2051" col2="3" start="477884" end="477886">#' </COMMENT>
  <COMMENT line1="2052" col1="1" line2="2052" col2="10" start="478117" end="478126">#' @export</COMMENT>
  <expr line1="2053" col1="1" line2="2099" col2="1" start="478350" end="489068">
    <expr line1="2053" col1="1" line2="2053" col2="15" start="478350" end="478364">
